A few weeks ago, the Consumer Protection Council (CPC) announced that it had suspended the operations of one of Nigeria’s favourite sweet tooth Krispy Kreme confectionary in Victoria Island for using expired doughnut fills. Read More: Lagosians React After CPC Shuts Down Kripsy Kreme Doughnuts In a recent development, the consumer council has announced that it has reopened the confectionary. An official statement signed by the Director-General, Babatunde Irukera, states that the outlet “satisfied that their operations and consumption of their product currently meets prevailing standards”. <img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-724707 lazyload" src="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-486x598.jpg" alt="" width="486" height="598" srcset="https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-486x598.jpg 486w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-937x1152.jpg 937w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-453x557.jpg 453w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-906x1114.jpg 906w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-195x240.jpg 195w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-390x480.jpg 390w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC-488x600.jpg 488w,https://guardian.ng/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/CPC.jpg 976w" sizes="(max-width: 486px) 100vw, 486px" />